title: MIND Food and Speed of Processing Training in Older Adults With Low Education, The MINDSpeed Alzheimer's Disease Prevention Pilot Trial
description_brief: The purpose of this study is to learn how foods high in polyphenols and brain training exercises affect older adults' cognitive performance
description_detailed:
Adults with low education who give informed consent will complete a baseline cognitive assessment and then be randomized to one of four arms: 1) MIND foods and cognitive training, 2) MIND foods and control training, 3) control foods and cognitive training, or 4) control foods and control training.

All interventions are conducted through applications running on a tablet computer device that we will provide to all participants for the study duration. Cognitive training is delivered through the online BrainHQ program from Posit Science, Inc. The foods will be shown on the tablet device in an online shopping format. Selected foods will be prepared and delivered by the study team.

Active intervention will last for 12 weeks. After the 12-weeks, free food deliveries will cease but participants who were allocated to cognitive training will continue to have access to BrainHQ. Those in the MIND food arms will be encouraged to maintain MIND food consumption.

participantFlowModule.preAssignmentDetails: Enrolled participants were excluded from the study before group assignment when Baseline assessment or Tablet Orientation could not be completed.

groups.title: MINDSpeed Intervention
groups.description:
Consumption of foods high in polyphenols (i.e., MIND foods) AND speed of processing training

Speed of processing training: Speed of processing training is provided by the Internet-based BrainHQ program from Posit Science, Inc. BrainHQ contains five different speed training modules (Hawk Eye, Visual Sweeps, Fine Tuning, Eye for Detail, Sound Sweeps) which tap time-order judgment, visual discrimination, spatial-match, forward-span, instruction-following, and memory.

MIND foods: The "MIND" diet (created by the Rush Aging \& Memory group) specifically emphasizes foods high in polyphenols such as berries, nuts, cocoa, black beans, olive oil, and green leafy vegetables. Participants select these foods from the digital study application and receive them through home delivery.

groups.title: MIND Food and Training Control
groups.description:
Consumption of foods high in polyphenols (i.e., MIND foods) AND online (inert) games

MIND foods: The "MIND" diet (created by the Rush Aging \& Memory group) specifically emphasizes foods high in polyphenols such as berries, nuts, cocoa, black beans, olive oil, and green leafy vegetables. Participants select these foods from the digital study application and receive them through home delivery.

Cognitive training control: Control training is provided by the Internet-based BrainHQ program from Posit Science, Inc.These are inert games such as tic-tac-toe, connect 4, battleship, etc.

achievements.comment: One participant was active in the study at the end of the Immediate Post-Training period, but did not complete the study visit due to health issues. Participant was still eligible to complete the Follow-Up period, but did not complete the follow-up assessment.

outcomeMeasures.title: Executive Cognitive Function Composite Score
outcomeMeasures.description: Executive Cognitive Function Composite Score as Measured by Individually-Administered Tests of Verbal Fluency, Complex Sequencing, Response Inhibition, and List Learning. The scale score range is -20 to 20. Low scores represent worse function and higher scores represent better function.

adverseEventsModule.timeFrame: Adverse events were collected from time of study enrollment (i.e., informed consent) until the participant completed the study at 6-Month Follow-Up or withdrew from the study, whichever came first.
adverseEventsModule.description: Participants were asked specifically about adverse events through structured questionnaire at Immediate Post-Training and Follow-Up study visits, though events were reported throughout the adverse event time frame as they became known to study staff.

explanation_target: Reason: The protocol describes a behavioral, multicomponent intervention consisting of consumption of foods high in polyphenols ("MIND" foods) plus speed-of-processing cognitive training aimed at improving cognitive performance and cognitive reserve in older adults — i.e., the intended effect is to improve cognition rather than to deliver a biologic or small-molecule that targets Alzheimer pathology. citeturn0search1turn1search4

Act: Key extracted details — (1) Intervention = high-polyphenol (MIND) foods and speed of processing training delivered via an iPad/online application (BrainHQ for speed training). citeturn0search1turn1search3 (2) Design = 2×2 randomized factorial pilot trial (MIND foods vs control foods × speed training vs control training), registered as NCT03419052. citeturn0search1turn1search4 (3) No drug, biologic, or small-molecule is administered; interventions are dietary/behavioral. citeturn0search1turn1search5 Based on these, the best-fit category is "Cognitive enhancer" because the primary goal is to improve cognitive performance/cognitive reserve rather than to target amyloid/tau with a biologic or small molecule, and the trial tests cognitive-training plus diet.

Reflect: The classification was checked against category definitions: this is not a biologic (no antibodies/vaccine) nor a small molecule pharmacologic agent, and it is not primarily targeting neuropsychiatric symptoms (e.g., agitation, depression). It is a prevention/intervention trial aiming to enhance cognition via diet and cognitive training, so "Cognitive enhancer" best matches. If you prefer strictly "drug-only" categories, one could mark this as 'N/A' because no pharmaceutical agent is involved — but given the category definitions allow cognitive-enhancing interventions, "Cognitive enhancer" is the appropriate classification. citeturn0search1turn1search4

Web search results / sources (selected): (1) Full protocol and methods for the MINDSpeed trial (MIND food + speed training) — Contemporary Clinical Trials / PMC article. citeturn0search1 (2) PubMed entry summarizing the trial. citeturn0search0 (3) Trial registry and summary (MedPath / ClinicalTrials entries for NCT03419052). citeturn1search4turn0search5 (4) ClinicalTrialsGPS / trial listing with dates and brief summary. citeturn1search3
explanation_agent: Reason: The intervention is behavioral/nutritional (MIND high-polyphenol foods) plus speed-of-processing cognitive training aimed to improve cognition and cognitive reserve — mechanisms are expected to act via enhancing synaptic function/plasticity and neuroprotection rather than targeting molecular AD pathologies (amyloid, tau, inflammation, etc.).

Act: Extracted details — (1) Intervention: MIND diet (high-polyphenol foods) + BrainHQ speed-of-processing training delivered via iPad/online; (2) Design: 2×2 randomized factorial pilot (MIND vs control foods × speed training vs control), NCT03419052; (3) No drug, biologic, or small molecule is administered — goal is cognitive enhancement/reserve. Based on these, the best CADRO match is M) Synaptic Plasticity/Neuroprotection because cognitive-enhancing behavioral and dietary interventions are intended to support synaptic function and neuroprotective processes.

Reflect: This classification fits the CADRO definitions better than A) Amyloid beta, B) Tau, F) Inflammation, or other pathology-focused categories because there is no explicit molecular target in those domains. Because the trial tests non-pharmacologic interventions designed to improve cognition via plasticity/neuroprotection, M) Synaptic Plasticity/Neuroprotection is the most specific appropriate CADRO category. If one required a strictly drug-only mapping, one could alternatively select 'T) Other' since no pharmacologic agent is used, but under CADRO's scope for cognitive-enhancing interventions, M is the best fit.

(3) Trial registry and summary (ClinicalTrials.gov NCT03419052). (4) ClinicalTrialsGPS / trial listing with dates and brief summary.
